l and Early Modern Times: Changing Paradigms, New Perspectives, Future Prospects -- tAfterword -- tContributors -- tAuthor Index -- tSubject Index -- tPrimary Sources Index0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis volume examines new developments in the fields of premodern Jewish studies over the last thirty years. The essays in this volume, written by leading experts, are grouped into four overarching temporal areas: the First Temple, Second Temple, Rabbinic, and Medieval periods. These time periods are analyzed through four thematic methodological lenses: the social scientific (history and society), the textual (texts and literature), the material (art, architecture, and archaeology), and the philosophical (religion and thought). Some essays offer a comprehensive look at the state of the field, while others look at specific examples illustrative of their temporal and thematic areas of inquiry. The volume presents a snapshot of the state of the field, encompassing new perspectives, directions, and methodologies, as well as the questions that will animate the field as it develops further. It will be of interest to scholars and students in the field, as well as to educated readers looking to understand the changing face of Jewish studies as a discipline advancing human knowledge  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 4aAntike. 4aHellenistisches Judentum. 4aJudaistik. 4aJüdische Kunst und Literatur. 7aRELIGION / Judaism / General.2bisacsh  aJewish literature.  aPremodern Judaism.  aart.  areligious studies.1 aAlpert Nakhai, Beth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBaskin, Judith R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrody, Robert, econtributor.